{"pageProps":{"post":{"creator":"Marc Reid","title":"Create a Disappearing Container","link":"https://datavis.blog/2022/06/30/create-a-disappearing-container-in-tableau/","pubDate":"Thu, 30 Jun 2022 09:48:23 +0000","content:encoded":"\n<p>The ability to show or hide a container was added in 2019.2 and allows you, for example, to take all your filters off the main dashboard making more space for charts. In this case the button to show the container is always visible on the dashboard so the user can always access the filters when needed.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>However, it’s also possible to put the show / hide button into the container itself so, when clicked, the container and the button both disappear. This may seem like an odd thing to do, but I’ve found it useful for creating short information messages that show when the dashboard first loads and that the user can dismiss when read, such as this <a href=\"https://tabsoft.co/3s7kquK\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">example</a> below:</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img data-attachment-id=\"3119\" data-permalink=\"https://datavis.blog/2022/06/30/create-a-disappearing-container-in-tableau/example-container/\" data-orig-file=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/example-container.png\" data-orig-size=\"1078,515\" data-comments-opened=\"0\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"example-container\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-medium-file=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/example-container.png?w=300\" data-large-file=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/example-container.png?w=736\" src=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/example-container.png?w=1078\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3119\" srcset=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/example-container.png 1078w, https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/example-container.png?w=150 150w, https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/example-container.png?w=300 300w, https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/example-container.png?w=768 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1078px) 100vw, 1078px\" /></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The advantage is that, after the container is closed, there is one less button sitting on the dashboard that will likely not be used again. It&#8217;s admittedly a niche use case but you might find it useful one day&#8230;</p>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Steps to create the disappearing container</h3>\n\n\n\n<ol><li>Bring a floating vertical container on to your dashboard</li><li>Add a show/hide button for the container</li><li>Add the button to the container</li><li>Add a text box under the button with your message</li><li>Resize and add left padding to the button&nbsp;</li></ol>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Item hierarchy in Tableau</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img data-attachment-id=\"3120\" data-permalink=\"https://datavis.blog/2022/06/30/create-a-disappearing-container-in-tableau/disappearing-container/\" data-orig-file=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/disappearing-container.png\" data-orig-size=\"1060,573\" data-comments-opened=\"0\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"disappearing-container\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-medium-file=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/disappearing-container.png?w=300\" data-large-file=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/disappearing-container.png?w=736\" src=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/disappearing-container.png?w=1060\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-3120\" srcset=\"https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/disappearing-container.png 1060w, https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/disappearing-container.png?w=150 150w, https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/disappearing-container.png?w=300 300w, https://datavisdotblog.files.wordpress.com/2022/06/disappearing-container.png?w=768 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1060px) 100vw, 1060px\" /></figure>\n\n\n\n<h3 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Video tutorial</h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Here&#8217;s a quick video walking through the process:</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"736\" height=\"414\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/uZqYKXF4V5w?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-gb&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation\"></iframe></div>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Thanks for watching!<br>Marc</p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-social-links has-icon-color has-icon-background-color is-style-default is-content-justification-left is-layout-flex wp-container-12\"><li style=\"color: #ffffff; background-color: #000000; \" class=\"wp-social-link wp-social-link-twitter wp-block-social-link\"><a rel=\" noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"